FT  15 MAY 93 / International Company News: Weak krona lifts Sandvik sales
by 27%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SANDVIK, the Swedish speciality steel and engineering group, stands by a
prediction of improved results for 1993 following a 3 per cent rise in
first-quarter profits to SKr486m (USDollars 65.76m).
The company said the downturn in European demand was more severe than
expected but this was offset by a further weakening of the krona.
Sales rose 27 per cent to SKr5.27bn, thanks to the weak krona, but were down
3 per cent excluding exchange rate movements. Group orders rose to SKr5.66bn
from SKr4.48bn.
Last year Sandvik reported a SKr1.53bn profit, down 20 per cent on 1991's
SKr1.92bn.
