<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 93 / International Company News: Minebea tumbles into the red and
suspends payouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MINEBEA, the world's leading maker of miniature bearings, reported a net
loss of Y64.8bn (Dollars 581m) for the six months ended March, following a
restructuring of its loss-making electronics operations.
The company, which made a Y2.1bn profit for the same period last year, said
sales rose 7 per cent to Y105bn, while pre-tax profit was 4 per cent higher
Y4.17bn. It will suspend dividend payments for the first time since 1965.
Minebea is now paying the price for an erratic diversification programme
which included a door-to-door cosmetics company, a semiconductor business,
and pig farms, all of which proved unsuccessful.
Sales of bearings and some electronics products have improved with a
recovery in computer demand in the US, while the sale of NMB Semiconductor,
to Nippon Steel should help to clear the balance sheet. First-half accounts
included a special loss of Y54bn related to that sale.
The company hopes the recovery in stock prices and a recently-announced
government spending package will stimulate domestic capital spending.
Minebea forecasts a 4.5 per cent rise in full-year sales to Y210bn, and 3
per cent growth in pre-tax profit to Y8.5bn.
Omron, a maker of control equipment, says pre-tax profits fell 48 per cent
to Y7bn in 1992-93.
</TEXT>
