<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 93 / UK Company News: Tadpole moves back into the black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TADPOLE Technology, the high technology group, made a profit in the first
six months reversing the trend of earlier years.
Before tax the figure for the half year to March 31 amounted Pounds 26,800
compared with a deficit of Pounds 1.4m a year ago. Turnover rose from Pounds
4.6m to Pounds 8.9m and the order book at period end stood at Pounds 5.5m.
Earnings per share of 0.3p compared with previous losses of 15.9p. The
group, based in Cambridge in the UK and Austin, Texas, is not paying a
dividend following the practice of high technology companies in the US which
rarely pay dividends in their early years.
The shares closed 22p down at 307p, but Mr Robert Booth, finance director,
said there had been speculative buying in the weeks leading up to the
interim results and the price was now back at its usual level. Tadpole moved
from the over-the-counter market to a full listing in December last year at
65p a share and swiftly shot up to the 300p mark.
Tadpole is a specialist in printer circuit board design and manufacture. It
has managed to combine the elements of a Sun Sparc work group station - the
workhorse of technical computing - in a notebook sized package called the
Sparcbook.
Mr George Grey, chief executive, said the results reflected growth of
Sparcbook sales coupled with a good performance from the printed circuit
board division.
The directors intend to appoint US financial advisers with the objective of
moving towards an ADR listing.
</TEXT>
