<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 93 / Germany warns Croatian leader: Clinton still hopes to win
over allies to military options on Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY, Croatia's most loyal supporter in Europe, yesterday warned Croatian
President Franjo Tudjman that he risked losing western support if he did
nothing to prevent the Bosnian Croats from attacking Moslems in Bosnia.
The German warning came as fighting between Croats and Moslems continued in
Mostar despite a ceasefire and as Serb forces pressed an attack against
Moslems near the strategically placed town of Brcko.
In Washington, meanwhile, President Bill Clinton said he would keep pushing
his proposals to lift the UN arms embargo, so that Bosnian Moslems can get
heavier weapons, and to use air power against Serb targets. His plan had
'not been rejected out of hand'. Some European allies had agreed with it and
'others are not prepared to go that far yet'. Mr Clinton also said he had
reservations about trying to set up and protect 'safe havens' for Moslems.
The warning to Croatia was delivered by Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign
minister, when he met Mr Tudjman in Zagreb. He was speaking both for his own
country and the whole EC, which earlier this week sent a similar message to
the Croatian president.
Mr Kinkel said the United Nations would shortly publish a report containing
evidence of direct Croatian involvement in the fighting in Bosnia between
Croats and Moslems, formerly allies in the struggle against the Bosnian
Serbs.
After two hours of talks with Mr Tudjman, the German minister said other
countries considered that Zagreb exerted decisive influence over the Bosnian
Croat militias, which are reported to be armed and financed from Croatia.
Though Mr Tudjman denied Zagreb bore any responsibility for Bosnian Croats'
acts, he told Mr Kinkel he would go to Mostar in the next few days to try to
persuade them to halt their attacks on Moslems.
A UN spokesman in New York said Mr Tudjman might meet Bosnian President
Alija Izetbegovic in Mostar next Tuesday to discuss how to end the fighting.
He said they had invited the international mediators, Lord Owen and Mr
Thorvald Stoltenberg, to attend. The mediators were expected to hold talks
in Moscow at the weekend and in London on Monday before flying to Bosnia.
Although fighting between Croats and Moslems continued in Mostar yesterday,
it was waged with less intensity than in the past few days. Spanish UN
troops came under fire as they tried to approach the line of confrontation
between the warring parties.
In the struggle between Serbs and Moslems in the north of the country, Serb
forces pushed forward towards the town of Brcko, which commands an important
supply route linking Serb territories in eastern and western Bosnia.
Moslem-controlled Sarajevo radio said more than 30 Serb tanks were trying to
break through Moslem lines near the town. Some 20 people had been killed in
the Serb offensive since Thursday and villages in the area had been
destroyed, the radio said.
</TEXT>
