<HEADLINE>
FT  15 MAY 93 / Germany's cool diplomat moves on
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major, the UK prime minister, recently invited him to 10 Downing
Street to say a special goodbye. The Sun, Britain's raucously xenophobic
best-selling daily paper, saluted him as 'a gem' in a farewell editorial.
(It also misspelled his name.)
'He's been a great success at a very difficult time. He's a harmoniser,'
says Sir Sigmund Sternberg, a member of the Board of Deputies of British
Jews, which - highly unusually - hosted a reception to bid him auf
Wiedersehen.
The man they are talking about is Mr Hermann von Richthofen, Germany's
ambassador to the UK. After a hectic 4 1/2 -year tenure, and plenty of
practice in weathering diplomatic squalls, he leaves London today to become
his country's ambassador to Nato.
Mr von Richthofen has made an impact for two reasons. First, he has
succeeded in presenting united Germany's human face not just to officials
but also to a broad cross-section of the British public.
In incidents ranging from disputes over German reunification with Mrs
Margaret (now Baroness) Thatcher to last autumn's row over Britain's exit
from the exchange rate mechanism, Mr von Richthofen has kept his cool under
fire.
In his Belgravia residence, Mr von Richthofen calls 'rock solid' the general
state of Anglo-German relations. 'We have had some irritations and some
disturbances, but they always went away very quickly.'
During his time in London, Germany has attracted flak for being too
aggressive - and also for not being aggressive enough. In 1991, in a unique
interview with the Sun, the ambassador defended his compatriots from charges
of being 'cowards' during the Gulf war, where Germany played a conspicuously
dormant role.
Since the ambassador appreciates British humour, he says he 'saw the funny
side' of his portrayal in the newspaper under the headline 'The Hun meets
the Sun'.
His worst moments, he says, came amid the recriminations after Britain's ERM
exit last September. 'When the Bundesbank was under unjust attack, you ask
yourself what have you done that you're so badly understood.'
He bristles slightly at the memory of his brusque invitation to explain to
the Foreign Office the leaking to the press of a document giving the
Bundesbank's version of events.
In spite of this episode, Mr von Richthofen says the Germans can learn from
the British 'to be more relaxed, more natural, not too pushy'.
What can Britain learn from Germany? The UK should pay more attention to
manufacturing industry and vocational training, the ambassador says, giving
engineers 'a higher position in the elite'.
Britain would also benefit from decentralisation. 'Giving regions and
municipalities more autonomy - this could also be something you could
learn.'
West Germany was established as a federal state after the second world war
partly as a result of British policy, Mr von Richthofen points out.
He adds a finely-weighed ounce of diplomatic judgment: 'We took your advice.
But, because of your different traditions, you didn't follow it up in your
own country.'
</TEXT>
