<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Poor inflation figures
sharply depress Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices fell sharply across the board yesterday after another bad
set of inflation figures sent bond prices tumbling for the second
consecutive day, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average retreated 34.32 from Wednesday's closing
record high to end at 3,447.99. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 5.57 at
439.23 and the Nasdaq composite receded 6.05 to 675.64. Trading volume on
the New York SE came to 294m shares.
After Wednesday's unexpectedly strong producer price inflation report,
yesterday it was the turn of the April consumer price index to scare the
markets. The CPI rose 0.4 per cent last month, above expectations, and the
'core' measure of consumer price inflation  - which excludes the volatile
food and energy components  - was also up a worrying 0.4 per cent.
The figures, which suggested that inflation is picking up alongside the
steadily growing economy, rattled Treasury investors, who sold bonds
heavily. In late trading, the benchmark 30-year bond was down well in excess
of a full point, and the yield was back up to almost 6.95 per cent.
The rise in bond yields and the fears of inflation hit stocks from the
opening, bringing the Dow average down sharply. The selling was apparent
across the board, although there was some refuge for investors in gold
shares, which traditionally act as a safe haven in inflationary times, and
metals issues, which are seen as beneficiaries of higher commodities prices.
A group of metals and gold stocks posted strong early gains, although some
late selling left them mixed at the close. Alcoa finished steady at Dollars
66, Newmont Mining climbed Dollars 1 5/8 but ended a net Dollars  1/2 down
at Dollars 50, Phelps Dodge put on Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 46, and
Homestake Mining firmed Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 17 7/8 , all in heavy
trading. On the American Stock Exchange, Pegasus Gold firmed Dollars 1 1/4
to Dollars 22 1/4 and Echo Bay Mines Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 11 1/8 .
Philip Morris bucked the wider market trend, rising Dollars  5/8 to Dollars
50 5/8 on 2.9m shares traded after Merrill Lynch raised its
intermediate-term rating on the stock from 'neutral' to 'above average'.
Motor shares declined in spite of more good news on car and truck sales.
General Motors slipped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 40 1/4 .
On the Nasdaq market, Apple ran against the grain, rising Dollars 2 1/4 to
Dollars 55 1/2 after the company unveiled the updated version of its
cross-platform multimedia architecture software, QuickTime for Windows.
Canada
THE US inflation news spurred solid gains in Canadian gold shares in very
heavy trading and more than offset losses in some other sectors, but
afternoon selling pulled the Toronto market well down from its intraday
high.
The TSE 300 index closed only 4.8 up at 3,801.3. Rises outscored declines by
432 to 322 after volume of 85.8m shares. The golds index rose 3 per cent as
the New York spot gold price climbed USDollars 7.30 an ounce to USDollars
368.55.
</TEXT>
