<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Foreign Exchanges: Iberian currencies are devalued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOTH THE Spanish peseta and the Portuguese escudo fell to the bottom of
their bands against the D-Mark in the European exchange rate mechanism
yesterday after their central banks announced plans to devalue the
currencies, writes James Blitz.
The Bank of Spain announced at 09.21 GMT yesterday that it was seeking a
meeting of the EC's monetary committee later that day for a realignment of
the ERM.
It was later announced that there would be an 8 per cent devaluation of the
Spanish peseta and a 6.5 per cent devaluation of the escudo against their
central Ecu rates.
Although dealers had anticipated that the peseta would be devalued either
before or after next month's Spanish elections, the timing of the move took
the markets by surprise.
Previous requests for devaluations have come at weekends, and the timing of
yesterday's move, at the start of an ERM trading day, suggested that the
Bank of Spain had suffered an excessively large drain on reserves when
trying to support the currency earlier in the week.
On Wednesday evening, one dealer at a major London bank said that the Bank
of Spain had spent a large amount of reserves maintaining its exchange rate
against the D-Mark. The Bank also bought back options to sell the German
currency, probably in the knowledge that these would become prohibitively
expensive to hedge after a devaluation.
The Bank of Spain's announcement was followed by strong selling of the
currency, which fell to Pta76.33 against the D-Mark from Wednesday's close
of Pta73.56. The escudo dropped similarly, moving as low as Esc98.23 to the
D-Mark from about Esc92.00 of the previous night.
The Iberian currency crisis had little immediate impact on the ERM as a
whole.
The Danish krone came under some selling pressure in the European afternoon,
being quoted as low as DKr3.8675 per D-Mark at one stage.
However, the overwhelming view in the market appeared to be that the
realignment of the Iberian currencies was a separate issue because of the
fundamental economic weakness of both countries.
According to Mr Avinash Persaud of UBS in London, the fate of both the krone
and the ERM will depend on whether the Danes vote 'no' in Tuesday's
referendum on the Maastricht treaty. 'Pressure on the Danish krone could
blow apart the ERM because there would be no fundamental explanation for
it,' he said.
Elsewhere in the currency markets, the dollar was firmer against the D-Mark
following a surprisingly big 0.4 per cent rise in US April consumer prices.
It closed at DM1.6145 from a previous DM1.6115. In New York the US currency
ended at DM1.6160.
Sterling remained weak, however, amid the poor political situation in the
UK. The pound closed at DM2.4625 from a previous DM2.4700.
</TEXT>
<XX>
