<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: ACP developing countries to
seek help from EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AFRICAN, Caribbean and Pacific developing countries are to seek European
Community help to revive international cocoa and coffee pacts, Reuter
reports from Brussels.
The recent collapse of talks on a new world coffee pact followed the failure
of negotiations on a new cocoa accord with a withholding scheme to support
prices. 'Prices have plummeted since the talks collapsed . . . we are trying
to enlist EC support to revive the accords,' General Ghebray Berhane, ACP
secretary, said yesterday. The ACP states begin a two-day ministerial
meeting in Brussels on Monday.
ACP officials said the loss in cocoa and coffee export earnings since 1985
was equal to the Ecu20bn (Pounds 15.75bn) of aid provided under the third
and fourth Lome Conventions, (1985-90) and (1990-2000), linking the EC with
69 ACP countries.
