<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Government Bonds: Spanish prices soar on devaluation move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEWS that the peseta would be devalued sent the Spanish government bond
market rocketing up yesterday in anticipation of interest rate cuts.
The actual devaluation figures  - 8 per cent for the peseta and 6.5 per cent
for the Portuguese escudo  - came out after the European markets closed.
Spanish bonds gained two points or more, with the shorter end feeling the
most benefit. Demand came from new investors and some switching out of
German bunds.
Although the devaluation was in the range of forecasts, it was significantly
ahead of the lower estimates of 6 per cent, adding to the feeling that there
would be further gains today.
At the longer end of the market, political uncertainty ahead of the general
election on June 6 was cited as one factor limiting the upside. Another was
the rise in inflation  - disappointing figures announced yesterday were not
quite drowned out by the peseta furore.
While Portuguese government bonds also registered gains, the illiquidity of
the market deterred investors.
The French government bond market was a little surprised at the swiftness of
the Bank of France's latest  1/4 point cuts in key interest rates but the
response was muted by continued nervousness ahead of the Danish referendum.
In Germany, two factors dampened the bond market after yesterday's rally on
the repo rate cut. One was the switching into Spain, the other some head
shaking by Bundesbank leaders over the prospect of accelerating rate cuts
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, central bank president, stressed the need the
maintain D-Mark stability. Hesaid 'a sledgehammer interest rate policy' was
inappropriate andearly gains in bunds were lost.
The day ended weakly for the UK market, which today expects the Bank of
England to make an announcement about the next gilt auction.
The 10-15 year area is forecast to be the target and roughly Pounds 3bn is
anticipated to keep up the relentless funding programme. The recent
faltering of the pound was seen as limiting overseas interest.
Reports of the death of Japan's benchmark government bond, the No 145 due
2002, seem to have been exaggerated. A revival of interest brought its yield
back below 4.5 per cent. It opened at 4.55 per cent and closed at 4.485 in
Tokyo. However, in overseas trading its fortunes waned again as it followed
US Treasuriesdownwards.
MORE BAD news on inflation sent longer-dated US Treasury securities into a
tailspin. The benchmark 30-year government bond was down 1 3/16 at 102 7/32
, yielding 6.946 per cent. At the short end of the market, the two-year note
was down  5/32 at 99 31/32 , to yield 3.874 per cent.
The news that sparked the sell-off at the long end was a
bigger-than-expected 0.4 per cent jump in the April consumer prices index
which, taken with Wednesday's news of an unexpected rise in the producer
prices index, reignited investors' fears of inflation. The 'core' measure of
consumer price inflation, excluding volatile food and energy prices, was
also strong, at up 0.4 per cent. Adding to market woes was news of April
retail sales up 1.2 per cent.
The decline in the long bond was exacerbated by concerns that the bad
inflation numbers would ruin the afternoon auction of Dollars 8.25bn in
30-year bonds. Although the auction subsequently went off smoothly, it was
not enough to pull the market off the bottom, which may also have been
disturbed by news of another strong set of weekly auto sales.
</TEXT>
<XX>
