<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / International Company News: Fininvest unveils SBE float
details
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FININVEST, the Italian media and financial services group controlled by Mr
Silvio Berlusconi, yesterday unveiled its long-awaited plan to list its
Silvio Berlusconi Editore publishing subsidiary.
The flotation of SBE is linked to an offer to shareholders in Mondadori,
Italy's biggest publishing group, to swap into SBE. The aim is to retain
Mondadori's identity while having SBE as the eventual single quoted vehicle
for Fininvest's publishing interests.
Analysts were surprised the transaction was not accompanied by a placing of
SBE stock by Fininvest to raise funds.
Such a placing is expected soon, with Fininvest eventually divesting up to
49 per cent of SBE's capital, although the first tranche may be smaller.
Trading in shares in Mondadori, which was suspended yesterday, is expected
to resume today or early next week.
Shareholders in Mondadori will be offered one SBE share for every one
Mondadori share held. Alternatively, they will be able to exchange four
Mondadori non-voting savings shares for three SBE shares. SBE has one equity
category.
The deal values Mondadori ordinary shares at L15,000 each, against a closing
price in Milan on Wednesday of L10,825, while savings shares are valued at
L11,250 each against a Wednesday close of L6,905. Should all Mondadori's
shareholders accept the deal, about 9.3 per cent of SBE will be floating.
The deal comes as part of a capital increase by SBE to L105bn (Dollars
68.8m) from L30bn, which will be subscribed by Fininvest in the form of
Mondadori shares.
The transaction marks a big strategy change for Mr Berlusconi, who has not
hidden his distaste for outside shareholders in his operations.
Only Mondadori and Standa, the retailing group bought by Fininvest in the
late 1980s, are quoted on the stock market.
The decision to float SBE and the expected placing of further stock reflects
Fininvest's need for cash to reduce borrowings and finance further
expansion. Mr Berlusconi is said to be keen to increase the size of his
group through acquisitions. However, Fininvest has been in a 'consolidation
phase' for some time owing to growing pressure on its financial resources.
Fininvest, which gained control of Mondadori after a battle for control with
Mr Carlo De Benedetti in 1990-91, owned almost 90 per cent of the ordinary
shares and 80 per cent of the savings stock. Last month it sold 20 per cent
of Mondadori's ordinary shares to SBE for L243.4bn.
</TEXT>
