<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / UK Company News: Mystery bidder gets in contact with
HunterPrint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUNTERPRINT, the specialist printer, revealed yesterday that it had been
contacted by an unidentified potential bidder for the group.
The sharp rise in the share price this week prompted the board to issue a
statement yesterday and bring forward the announcement of HunterPrint's
interim results by a week.
In the statement Mr Jeoff Samson, chairman, said the company had been
contacted by third parties, but that the contacts were at a preliminary
stage and 'may or may not lead to an offer being made for the company.'
HunterPrint's share price had risen from 64p at the end of last week to 75p
at the close on Wednesday. It gained another 5p yesterday to close at 80p,
valuing the group at Pounds 46.3m.
Mr Samson, who together with Mr Tony Caplin, chief executive, pushed through
a refinancing package including a Pounds 20m rights issue late last year,
said the board had been advised to make the statement following the share
price increase.
For the six months to end-March HunterPrint showed a turnround in
profitability following the restructuring. The group returned profits of
Pounds 330,000 pre-tax compared with a Pounds 3.85m loss in the year-ago
period.
Sales fell by 7.5 per cent to Pounds 26.6m (Pounds 28.8m) reflecting the
continuing difficult trading conditions in the group's sector of the
printing industry.
Nevertheless, a Pounds 2.3m loss on ordinary activities before interest was
turned into a Pounds 909,000 profit in the latest six months and net
interest charges fell from Pounds 1.54m to Pounds 579,000 reflecting the
improved state of the balance sheet following the refinancing and rescue
rights issue  - HunterPrint's second in two years.
The first involved Sir Ian MacGregor, who was ousted as chairman in August.
Mr Samson said the greater financial stability and strength had enabled the
group to increase its customer base and generate additional orders from
existing clients.
Contract orders at the group's Corby printing site now account for 50 per
cent of the workload compared with 39 per cent 12 months ago.
However, Mr Samson said the markets served by the Corby site  - newspapers,
publishing and direct mail  - showed no signs that 1993 would produce better
prices. The spot market remained very competitive and margins on spot work
continued to be under pressure.
Similarly, the Hardy Business Forms subsidiary continued to experience
difficult market conditions, but managed to return to 'modest' profitability
in the first half.
</TEXT>
