<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / GPA must raise Dollars 250m in a week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GPA GROUP, the troubled aircraft leasing company, needs to raise Dollars
250m (Pounds 162m) within a week before its rescue deal with GE Capital can
go ahead.
While the company's core lenders yesterday welcomed the last-minute
agreement with General Electric's financial services arm, they said GPA
needed to overcome a number of hurdles.
GPA yesterday told its bondholders, in a meeting in New York, that its board
would decide by Monday whether it would be able to close the deal with GE
Capital, enabling it to finance bond payments due over May and June.
GE Capital has yet to agree what price it will pay for its option to take a
65 per cent stake in the group, which could rise to 80 per cent by the end
of March 1997. However, it may insist that the banks write off at least 20
per cent of their Dollars 3bn borrowings as part of any deal to take a
controlling stake.
In the next few days the group's key lenders will be asked to provide
Dollars 100m as a bridging loan to help finance the bond payments. Some
existing shareholders will also be asked to provide a further Dollars 150m.
The total of Dollars 250m must be found before May 17, when the first
Dollars 50m of bond payments are due.
GPA's 138 banks will also have to provide further waivers of breaches on its
banking covenants until the end of June.
While most lenders are expected to agree, the group is not taking any bank
for granted given that four have still not agreed to the restructuring of
GPA's Dollars 5.5bn of borrowings.
The group also requires a waiver over the same period from the holders of a
Japanese club loan, worth Dollars 150m, with further extentions needed later
in the year. Harris Investment Management, a subsidiary of the Chicago-based
Harris Banking Corp, must waive its Dollars 45m put option.
GPA has warned its banks that the combined cost of restructuring, lost
deposits from aircraft manufacturers and falling aircraft values will lead
to provisions which could be Dollars 500m.
GE Capital has agreed in principle to buy Dollars 1.35bn worth of aircraft
from GPA. The group's bondholders are being advised by Blackstone Group, the
US investment bank which specialises in company restructuring, and lawyers
Wachtell, Lipton. Lazard Freres stepped down from advising bondholders
because it was trading the bonds.
The refinancing, Page 20
</TEXT>
