<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / GrandMet helped by devaluation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BOOST of Pounds 29m from sterling's devaluation helped lift first-half
pre-tax profits of Grand Metropolitan, the food, drinks and retailing group,
from Pounds 394m to Pounds 416m, a rise of 5.6 per cent.
At level exchange rates, profits would have declined 1.8 per cent.
GrandMet's shares lost 11p to close at 422p.
Currency translation of dollar-denominated debt also added Pounds 676m to
the group's net borrowings which rose to Pounds 3.16m, increasing gearing
from 70 per cent to 82 per cent.
Sir Allen Sheppard, chairman and chief executive, said trading had remained
challenging and the pace of recovery in key markets remained difficult to
predict. 'We expect the US and UK to continue to improve gradually; but we
believe the continental European markets will increasingly be affected by
recession throughout 1993.'
Earnings per share for the six months to March 31 improved 3 per cent to
13.4p; the interim dividend is up 5.4 per cent to 4.85p.
The North American food business reported profits of Pounds 126m, 5 per cent
ahead in sterling but 10 per cent lower in local currency. Dollar profits of
the US Green Giant vegetable business were halved as the industry continued
to work through the surplus produced last summer and the market remained
'extremely soft and competitive'. The group is expanding into the fresh
produce market with sales of Green Giant vegetables of more than Dollars 50m
(Pounds 32.4m).
Operating profit from European food operations, affected by marketing
investments in Haagen-Dazs ice-cream and Pillsbury dough, as well as
deteriorating market conditions, fell from Pounds 4m to Pounds 1m.
IDV, the drinks division, contributed profits of Pounds 268m, 4 per cent
ahead in local currency. The group strengthened its market share in North
America where profits rose from Pounds 77m to Pounds 92m.
On the retailing side, Burger King moved profits 13 per cent up to Pounds
63m.
In the UK, the Chef &amp; Brewer managed pubs and GrandMet Estates, the property
division, raised profits 8 per cent to Pounds 28m though pub volumes were
lower.
GrandMet, which included a Pounds 6m trading loss from the Inntrepreneur
pubs joint venture with Courage in its accounts, announced that, subject to
revaluation, it will have to inject a further Pounds 65m into the company in
October to comply with banking covenants.
Inntrepreneur funding, Page 24
</TEXT>
