<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Clarke U-turn over court fines: Home secretary's policy
shift seen as fillip for demoralised backbenchers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN, ALAN PIKE and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is to abandon the controversial unit fines system. The
decision, announced yesterday, represents a surprise U-turn by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, home secretary.
The government intends to enact its proposed changes immediately by
incorporating them into the latest Criminal Justice Bill, due to start its
committee stage later this month.
The decision to rush through the proposals partly reflects the government's
need to lift the spirits of backbenchers demoralised by last week's election
disasters. Mr Clarke was encouraged by loud Tory cheers when he made his
statement.
Unit fines, under which individuals pay penalties according to their income,
have led to some people with above-average earnings being fined thousands of
pounds for relatively minor offences. They were introduced only in October,
and on May 4 Mr Clarke reiterated his support for the principle, but said
the banding on which the fines operated needed amending.
He told the Commons yesterday, however, that he had decided to abolish the
system altogether, as he had reached the conclusion that it would be
impossible to modify it satisfactorily. Magistrates will still be encouraged
to consider individuals' incomes when setting penalties, but there will be
no specific formula.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said he had never seen so quick a
collapse of government policy. 'Having spent weeks, if not months, robustly
telling us that the Criminal Justice Act had a lot to commend it, you now
equally robustly tell us today that you must scrap its central provisions.'
Unit fines were introduced under the 1991 Criminal Justice Act, the main
thrust of which was to encourage more imaginative penalties and avoid the
unnecessary use of custody. Mr Clarke, announcing a number of changes to the
act yesterday, adopted a different emphasis  - the need to tighten the
criminal law to give courts more powers to deal with offenders.
Other changes will include relaxing restrictions on taking previous records
into account, tightening the granting of bail, and increasing the maximum
penalty for causing death by dangerous driving from five to ten years.
The decision to change the act so soon will dismay penal reform
organisations and many criminal justice professionals. Only this week, the
National Association of Probation Officers urged the government to consult
widely before repealing any part of the act.
</TEXT>
