<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Letter: Audit fee figures not just simple averages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr J DENNIS HENRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Andrew Jack, in his article on international accounting and auditing
(Accountancy Column, May 6), quoted an average of audit fees as a proportion
of sales as being 0.022 per cent in the UK, according to the Cifar report.
This average is only true for companies of a particular size; those with
Pounds 20m-Pounds 50m in sales. The median figure for small plcs, with less
than Pounds 5m in sales, is about 0.0056 per cent, while companies with more
than Pounds 1bn in sales have a median of only 0.00046 per cent.
The industry sector also has a big effect. Distribution companies can, for
example, have audit fees one third those of similar-sized engineering
companies.
I give the above figures as many may have compared their own percentage with
that given and found variations. As ever, the use of simple averages can be
misleading.
J Dennis Henry,
JDH Consultants,
11 Clydebrae Drive,
Bothwell,
Glasgow G7 8SB
</TEXT>
