<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The usual undemanding Friday night schedule. It's good news for voyeurs with
the return of Through the Keyhole (ITV, 7pm) in which the much caricatured
David Frost and the even more caricatured Loyd Grossman join forces to take
a prying camera into the homes of semi-celebrities, while nosy panellists
try and guess the name of the house owner. Also a return for Rides (BBC1,
9.30pm), the tribulations of an all-female minicab firm.
Am I alone in finding Have I Got News For You (BBC2, 10pm) unwatchable? The
desperate attempts of the regulars to find innuendo in every item; the
embarrassed silences of the guests; and the hysterical baying of the
audience make it a masterpiece of artificial pretension.
A surfeit of self-congratulation continues with Clive Anderson Talks Back
(C4, 10.30pm). The witty barrister makes sure he has the punchlines,
treating his guests as fall guys.
Anyone who failed to get a ticket for Leonard Cohen's Albert Hall concerts
this week can catch the lugubrious Canadian on Later with Jools Holland
(BBC2, 11.15pm).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4832 Radio Broadcasting Stations.
    P4833 Television Broadcasting Stations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
