<PROFILE>_AN-DENCNAC4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930514
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Abta payouts challenged: Travel companies seek injunction to
stop cut in customer refunds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIX TRAVEL companies have applied for an injunction requiring the
Association of British Travel Agents to withdraw a threat to limit
repayments to customers of failed school-trip operators.
The application follows a letter Abta sent to education authorities last
month saying the association had decided to limit the losses it suffered
when school-tour operators, particularly those offering ski holidays,
failed.
A High Court hearing on the application began last Tuesday and finished
yesterday. The six companies  - Travelbound, Equity, Campus Centres, Ski
Partners, Seasun Holidays and STS Travel  - are awaiting judgment.
Since setting up its system of consumer protection in the mid-1970s, Abta
has said it will ensure that customers are repatriated and their deposits
repaid when member companies fail. Abta members have bonds to protect
customers, but when these prove inadequate the association's insurance makes
up the shortfall.
But in 1991 the association came close to financial collapse when it had to
make repayments to parents who had paid for ski trips organised by companies
which folded. In its letter, the association said it had paid out almost
Pounds 12m to parents over the past three years.
It said that deposits paid after April 23 this year would not be protected
if paid more than 12 months in advance. If paid less than a year in advance
they would only be protected up to Pounds 25 a head. The balance of payment
would be protected only if it was paid less than 10 weeks before departure.
The association subsequently wrote to education authorities and schools
pointing out that the limits only applied where failed companies' bonds were
inadequate.
The restrictions applied to coach and ferry trips only. Charter flight
holidays would still be protected fully by Air Travel Organisers' Licences,
administered by the Civil Aviation Authority.
Mr Andrew Lay, Travelbound's commercial director, said the letters had
caused confusion. He said: 'At present, everyone believes if they book a
holiday with Abta their money is secure.'
</TEXT>
