<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Coopers probed on Maxwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COOPERS &amp; LYBRAND, the accountancy firm, is to be scrutinised as part of a
wide-ranging investigation into the Maxwell affair by the accountancy
profession's highest disciplinary body.
The Joint Disciplinary Scheme is to investigate the circumstances
surrounding pensions transactions within the business empire of the late
Robert Maxwell.
The scheme rarely launches investigations and only holds them for serious
issues that command a high level of public interest.
Just two investigations are under way: into Barlow Clowes and Bank of Credit
and Commerce International.
The scheme is operated jointly by the chartered accountancy organisations
for England, Wales and Scotland and the Chartered Association of Certified
Accountants.
It has the power to examine and discipline member firms and any individual
members in either public practice or commercial work.
A committee of inquiry is being selected for the Maxwell case and the formal
announcement of an investigation is likely to be made within the next two
months.
In the meantime, the newly appointed 'executive counsel' will examine the
background to the case and prepare evidence before submitting it to the
committee.
The Maxwell investigation has been triggered by a referral from the
Securities and Investments Board last summer to the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales, which has in turn passed it on to the
scheme.
It will examine pensions transactions relating to Bishopsgate Investment
Management, London and Bishopsgate Investment Management and a further 10 or
more companies in the group. More than Pounds 440m was stolen from the
pensions funds.
Details of the Maxwell inquiry emerged in the latest annual report from the
scheme, which was circulated yesterday.
The accounts for the year to December 31 1992 show expenditure of Pounds 1m,
which is exactly offset by income, including Pounds 142,000 recoverable from
fines and costs awarded.
There have been 33 referrals to the committee, 31 completed investigations
and 15 appeals since the scheme was founded in 1979.
</TEXT>
