<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Britain's pay and benefits costs low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S employment costs are among the lowest in western Europe, research
on average pay and benefits shows.
The study, by actuarial consultants Noble Lowndes, found that Britain's
employment costs - comprising pay, social security contributions, income tax
paid by employees, and voluntary and mandatory supplementary benefits - are
only marginally higher than Spain's.
The comparison of likely living standards upon retirement shows that state
social security plus private pension provisions will earn the average Briton
77 per cent of net earnings at retirement. This compares with 93 per cent
for Dutch pensioners, 91 per cent for Italian pensioners and 75 per cent for
German pensioners.
The costs of social security in Britain are also more evenly spread between
employer and employee than in some other EC states. UK employers pay 40 per
cent of social costs while in Italy they pay 70 per cent.
Sweden and Switzerland respectively are the most expensive countries when
pay and social costs are considered against the purchasing power of the
local currency.
In Sweden, for instance, for each Skr100 of take-home pay, an employer must
allocate a further Skr105 to cover social costs. In the UK, the employer
must provide an additional Pounds 67 for every Pounds 100 of take-home pay.
1993 Guide to Pensions and Labour Law in Europe. Noble Lowndes and Partners,
PO Box 144, Norfolk House, Wellseley Road, Croydon, CR9 3EB. Pounds 40.
</TEXT>
