<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Wales picks up foreign plums: How the inward investment
trend is being bucked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR David Hunt, Welsh secretary, was banging the drum this week over foreign
investment in Wales.
The occasion was the 20th anniversary of the first arrival in Wales of a
Japanese company.
More striking was the fact that last year foreign direct investment in Wales
was higher than the year before.
This seems a remarkable exception to the general trend. Foreign investment
in Europe reached its peak at the end of the 1980s. Since then it has
dropped sharply, both in the European Community and in the UK overall.
But in Wales, according to Mr Hunt's officials, last year's figure of Pounds
825m for planned investment by foreign companies was 13 per cent up on 1991
and more than double the 1990 level.
Mr Hunt says that with only 5 per cent of the population, Wales has claimed
20 per cent of inward investment into the UK. This investment has more than
compensated for blows during the 1980s such as the closure of the Shotton
steelworks in Clwyd, north Wales.
Last year UK manufacturing output was 5 per cent higher than in 1979. Welsh
output, says Mr Hunt, was 27 per cent higher.
In seeking to define Wales' success in attracting foreigners Mr Hunt points
first to the quality of the Welsh workforce: 'I think the work ethic is the
most important factor. In Wales we've always had a tradition of working hard
and of long service with one employer. If you talk to a German company like
Bosch they will say their productivity in Wales is higher than it is in
Germany.'
Yet other UK regions could make similar claims. A more revealing difference
is the advantage Wales derives from the centralisation of functions in the
Welsh Office.
'We are the ultimate one-stop shop,' Mr Hunt says. 'An inward investor just
has to come to me or one of my colleagues. He doesn't need to see anyone
else.
'We bring everybody together, whether it's the Welsh Development Agency, the
local authority, the Training and Enterprise Council or the university.
'At the Welsh Office we have all the policies brought together  - education,
health, environment, industry, agriculture, transport and training.'
Mr Hunt takes an aggressive approach to marketing: 'I'm about to fly off at
the end of the month to North America where we have some very good
prospects.
'They all involve competition with other parts of Europe, not the UK.
'I'm generally fighting Ireland in particular, because they go out
positively to win manufacturing, and Spain.
'Belgium is getting very positive about investment too, and parts of France
are going out more savagely to win business.'
Above all, he says: 'I believe we combine better than any other country in
Europe. Led by the secretary of state and the chairman of the Welsh
Development Agency we go into boardrooms anywhere in the world and argue the
case for Wales. There aren't many other parts of the world that do that.'
 -----------------------------------------------------
FOREIGN INVESTMENT IN WALES
 -----------------------------------------------------
                      Planned        Number of
                   (Pounds m)         projects
 -----------------------------------------------------
1989                      476               48
1990                      402               77
1991                      733               90
1992                      825               83
 -----------------------------------------------------
Source: Welsh Office
