<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Private company aids tax reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INLAND REVENUE has awarded a private management consultancy a 10-week
contract to help with its plans for reforming the personal tax system.
P-E International, based in Egham, Surrey, has been awarded an initial
Pounds 150,000 contract for five staff to review the Revenue's strategy and
make recommendations on how it will be implemented.
If the work meets with Revenue approval, the company is likely to be awarded
a further three-year contract believed to be worth about Pounds 2.25m.
The second stage will cover support, analysis and advice on the changes
required in Revenue processes, internal organisation and information
technology.
It will primarily focus on simplification of the self-assessment personal
tax system, but also provide support for wider aspects of the current
internal restructuring of the Revenue.
The proposals for self-assessment of personal tax - which will affect up to
4m self-employed people and a similar number of other taxpayers - have been
heralded in two consultative documents and most recently in the chancellor's
Budget speech. They are due to be introduced for the 1996-97 tax year.
The appointment is the result of a recent public competition for the
contract, and follows wide-ranging proposals for reforms of the system of
self-assessment.
The system will introduce a method that is already in place in some
countries, such as the US, by which taxpayers estimate their own tax
liability and submit their tax forms to the Revenue along with payment.
At present the Revenue makes an assessment after taxpayers have returned
their forms, and a request for payment is sent out.
The Revenue hopes that the changes will reduce the demands on its time and
manpower from inquiries by taxpayers.
</TEXT>
