FT  14 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Backing for terror insurance
measure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPS LAST night signalled that terrorist attacks would not be allowed to
wreck the operations of commerce and industry as the Reinsurance (Acts of
Terrorism) bill cleared all its Commons stages in just over three hours,
Ivor Owen writes.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said that even with the latest
increases, insurance premiums still represented a very small proportion of
total business costs and were good value overall.
He said the typical extra terrorism premium on a city-centre office block
insured for Pounds 10m would be Pounds 8,000 a year  - and the maximum would
be Pounds 12,000 a year.
Mr Hamilton confirmed that the bill, an enabling measure, would give effect
to the draft agreement establishing the Pool Reinsurance company.
