FT  14 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Clarke rules out bugging inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH CLARKE yesterday ridiculed Labour calls for an investigation into
allegations that the security services had eavesdropped on members of the
royal family. He said there was not a 'shred' of evidence to support them.
The home secretary responded witheringly to demands from Mr Tony Blair for
an 'urgent investigation', accusing his Labour opposite number of being a
'tabloid politician'.
It was 'absolutely absurd' for MPs to be 'taking up this kind of nonsense at
the behest of the tabloid newspapers'. He would investigate claims that the
moon was made of green cheese if Labour could find a crumb of evidence to
support that theory.
Mr Blair said that either the transcripts circulating were forgeries, 'in
which case there has almost certainly been a serious offence of criminal
fraud', or they were genuine, 'in which case a gross intrusion of privacy by
illegal means' had taken place.
Cabinet ministers agreed yesterday to proceed in the next session of
parliament with legislation to put MI6 on a statutory basis. Restrictions
are also expected on media bugging devices and telephoto lenses and trespass
on private property.
But the government has not so far decided whether to bow to pressure from
MPs and agree to the setting up of a special scrutiny committee for MI5 and
MI6.
