<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Committee attacks 'lack of
long-term policy on EC'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Commons foreign affairs committee yesterday implicitly criticised the
government for its lack of a long-term policy on the European Community and
recommended early steps to clarify its ideas on the subject, Robert Mauthner
writes.
In its second report on Europe after Maastricht, the committee also called
for improved contacts between the European parliament and national
parliaments, though stressing that the latter should not become subordinate
to the Strasbourg parliament.
'The United Kingdom needs to decide what sort of European Community it wants
and to push for it,' the report said. 'Planning for this should begin
immediately after the Maastricht treaty is ratified, to avoid being put in a
position of simply reacting to ideas from other member states.'
The committee also recommended that the House of Commons be given greater
opportunities to express its views to the executive on proposals for
Community action.
The Commons would need to re-examine its role in respect of EC legislation,
particularly in the light of the enhanced legislative powers given to the
European parliament under the terms of the Maastricht treaty.
Given the conflicting views about how the principle of subsidiarity would be
applied, and as a way of associating the Commons more closely with the
European Community's legislation, the committee recommended that the
government report regularly to the House.
This could take the form of six-monthly reports on 'developments in the
European Community', setting out the way the principle of subsidiarity was
being applied.
The principle states that the Community should take decisions only on
matters which cannot be dealt with more effectively by national governments.
</TEXT>
