<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Union urges workers not to abandon hope: Plea to carry on
working
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A day of bizarre events, it was one of the most extraordinary scenes:
2,000 people, last survivors of a north-east industry which was once supreme
in the world, standing in the driving rain to hear their union leaders urge
them not to give up hope, but to resume work.
Mr Tommy Brennan, regional organiser of the GMB general union, addressed the
workforce beside an empty slipway.
'The membership have given us their full commitment to continue to work
normally in the hope the receiver can attract a buyer, an interested party,
to take on the running of the company,' he said later.
The workforce, he said, was angry. 'But there's a realisation today, most
important of all, that we must keep it going,' he added.
In the Commons Mr John Major, the prime minister, said Swan's tender for a
vital contract was rejected because it was 'many tens of millions of pounds'
above the rival bid.
He expressed regret at the result, but pointed to the measures announced on
Wednesday, including a new enterprise zone. 'It is precisely because we are
concerned about the employment prospects at Tyneside that we announced the
range of measures yesterday,' he said.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said the government had
been warned for six months of what was going to happen. By failing to allow
Swan access to European intervention funds to help it move into merchant
shipbuilding, it had denied the yard a future, he said.
Mr Neville Trotter, Tynemouth MP and the only local Tory MP, concentrated on
prospects for new jobs. 'What we have got to do now is co-ordinate our
efforts to ensure that everything possible is done to provide alternative
employment.'
Mr Stephen Byers, Labour MP for Wallsend, said Swan was condemned to
closure. 'It's come about because of a deliberate decision made by the
government. When they talk about the market you should remember the
government is the market because they place the orders,' he said.
Mr Byers said the opposition would lead a half-day debate next Wednesday on
redundancies in the defence industry.
</TEXT>
