<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Japan irked by rejection of whale plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A JAPANESE request for a harvest of 50 whales in its coastal waters was
rejected yesterday by member nations of the International Whaling
Commission, which are still deeply divided over a controversial proposal for
a sanctuary in the southern oceans.
Japanese officials again threatened that the country would leave the IWC if
it continues to rule against a limited resumption of commercial whaling,
while the commission has virtually split into two camps and is unable to
agree on when to discuss sensitive issues, let alone to agree on decisions.
A majority of the 34 nations represented at the IWC's annual meeting in
Kyoto supported a resolution condemning the 'research' whaling programmes of
Norway and Japan, which last year caught 330 minke whales in the Antarctic
region. The vote annoyed Japanese representatives, who argue that the
research is necessary to ensure the health of the whale population.
Japanese officials were also unhappy that a majority of nations voted
against the quota of 50 whales under a scheme known as community-based
whaling. Tokyo had hoped to win approval for the concept of community
whaling, which, it says, would involve the local consumption of whale
products and not commercial sales.
But in spite of the setbacks, and the threats to leave the IWC, UK and US
officials expect that Japan will remain in the commission, as it would be a
loss of face for the country to withdraw when hosting the annual meeting.
Tokyo is also known to be wary of irritating the US government, which is
taking a strong line on environmental issues.
The commission's meeting is due to end today, and its reputation will suffer
if member countries are unable to agree to vote on the sanctuary proposal or
on a management scheme for whale stocks, supposed to be concluded at this
gathering.
Five nations, including Brazil and Sweden, proposed that the sanctuary vote
be deferred for a year, but supports of the sanctuary, which would last for
50 years and be reviewed after 10 years, are still pushing for vote even
though they are certain not to get the three-quarters majority required.
</TEXT>
