FT  14 MAY 93 / Russian industrial plan to be redrafted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RUSSIAN government yesterday failed to agree a long-promised industrial
policy because of divisions over how generous the cash-strapped state can be
as it tries to tackle inflation.
At yesterday's cabinet meeting older conservatives disagreed among
themselves rather than clashing with young monetarist-minded radicals. The
cabinet ordered the redrafting of a plan which was supposed to provide
selective support for industry after Mr Oleg Lobov, first deputy prime
minister in charge of the economy, widened it to support virtually all
economic sectors.
Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, prime minister, said the plan had to focus on
priority sectors as the state had to avoid fuelling inflation by printing
money.
Mr Ivan Materov, the deputy economic minister, who presented the plan to the
cabinet, said its intention was to support areas which did not enjoy demand
now but would do so once the economy pulled out of its 'deep depression'.
