<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / BT profits fall Pounds 1bn on cost of job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Telecommunication's heavy redundancy costs caused a Pounds 1.1bn
fall in its pre-tax profits to Pounds 1.98bn for the year ended March and
contributed to a worse-than-expected deficit in its pension fund.
Changes in advanced corporation tax in the March Budget and dividend income
lower than forecast were additional factors in the Pounds 750m pension fund
deficit, foreshadowing similar pressure on other companies' pension funds.
BT topped up its fund and resumed corporate contributions at the beginning
of this financial year but the impact on profits is likely to be moderate,
analysts said.
The salary of Mr Iain Vallance, BT's chairman, is to be frozen at Pounds
465,000 and will not be reviewed again until July 1994. The
performance-related component remains unchanged at Pounds 90,000.
Despite the recession, turnover was only slightly lower at Pounds 13.24bn.
Underlying turnover growth of 2.8 per cent in the final quarter led BT to
claim it had 'turned the corner quite significantly'.
An 8.3 per cent increase in net dividend payments and the strong cashflow of
the business pleased the City.
Analysts were untroubled by the unexpected size of the pension fund deficit.
BT's shares closed 1.5p up, at 404p, encouraging news for the government as
it prepares to sell a third tranche of its BT shares in July.
The pre-tax profits of Pounds 1.98bn were after Pounds 1.03bn in charges for
the voluntary redundancy scheme which reduced BT's workforce by 19 per cent
over the year to 171,000. Disposals and the repurchase of bonds reduced
profits by a further Pounds 190m.
BT proposed a final dividend of 9.45p to make a total of 15.6p a share, up
8.3 per cent up on the previous year. Earnings per share fell to 19.8p from
33.2p.
Lex, Page 18
BT pension scheme, Page 19
Cloud with silver lining, Page 21
</TEXT>
