<HEADLINE>
FT  14 MAY 93 / Women's pensions bill main casualty of legislative line-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICALLY sensitive plans to raise the state retirement age for women were
postponed by Cabinet ministers yesterday as they agreed a programme for next
year aimed at calming Tories with populist measures on crime and
deregulation.
The pensions equalisation bill was the biggest casualty as agreement was
reached on the legislative programme for the parliamentary session starting
in November.
A white paper, expected to recommend raising the state pension age for women
from 60 to 65 sometime next century, is now not likely until autumn.
Also delayed until the 1994-95 session at least is legislation on
privatising the Post Office.
But Cabinet ministers gave the go ahead to three Home Office bills  - on
Sunday trading, tougher penalties against juvenile and other criminals, and
restructuring the police service.
Mr John Major will today try to restore an impression of stable government
after the serious buffeting of the last week following disastrous
by-election and local election results. In spite of government U-turns this
week on schools testing and yesterday on the unit fines system, the prime
minister will seek to assure party activists at the Scottish Tory party
conference that he is determined to carry through the policies to which
Tories are pledged.
Mr Major will claim that a commitment to combat crime is an enduring
strength of the Conservative party and will promise all policies will be
geared towards a sustainable economic recovery.
The prime minister's office rebuffed suggestions the government had slimmed
down its legislative plans in the face of growing dissent within Tory ranks.
Adding to government difficulties was the death yesterday of Mr Robert
Adley, Tory MP for Christchurch, cutting the party's majority to 18.
The swing Liberal Democrats need to overturn his 23,000 majority is less
than the party achieved in last week's Newbury by-election.
Between 15 to 20 bills are expected for the parliamentary session beginning
in November. A bill on banking supervision promised after the collapse of
the Bank of Credit and Commerce International has been suspended.
But measures agreed for next year include a deregulation bill, drawn up by
the Department of Trade and Industry, but including the deregulation of
London buses.
The Foreign Office has won space for a bill to put the overseas security
service MI6 on a statutory basis. But the government has yet to decide on
whether to increase the accountability of MI6 and its domestic counterpart
MI5 to parliament.
A bill is expected on restricting media use of bugging and telephoto lenses
 - although ministers will deny it has been approved in response to claims
that the Royal family has been bugged.
Certain to be included, however, is legislation restricting the availability
of invalidity benefit, restructuring of Scottish and Welsh local councils,
privatising British Coal, setting up an environment protection agency,
reforming teacher training and ending the monopoly of the National Union of
Students.
Unit fines dropped, page 18
</TEXT>
